"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/851710","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2018-03-09","<p>The Department uses multiple channels to publicise information about Universal Credit.</p><p> </p><p>Our successful Opening Up Work promotion campaign is advertising Universal Credit to people who may need to claim. This includes digital advertising, posters at bus stops and in transport hubs, posters in shopping precincts, videos in GP surgeries and Post Offices, and local radio and press advertising.</p><p> </p><p>To further raise awareness, we place promotional products, such as posters and leaflets, in jobcentres, including recent products to increase awareness about the availability of advances.</p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2018-03-09T11:26:04.183Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/851710/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/851710/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/851710/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2018-02-28","Universal Credit: Zero Hours Contracts","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what steps her Department is taking to ensure that low-paid workers on zero-hours contracts are aware of their entitlement to universal credit.","false","Biography information for Frank Field","Birkenhead","Frank Field","130473"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/851711","HM Treasury","false","2018-03-05","<p>In addition to observing the usual ISA regulations, for an individual to qualify for a Help to Buy: ISA they must be 16 or over, have a valid National Insurance number, be a UK resident, and be a first-time buyer. Under this scheme being a first-time buyer means they must not have owned a property anywhere in the world.</p><p>An individual will then qualify for a government bonus when they come to buy a property if it is:</p><p>a) in the UK;</p><p>b) costs less than £250k (or £450k in London);</p><p>c) will be their only home;</p><p>d) is where they intend to live; and</p><p>e) will be purchased with a mortgage.</p>","Salisbury","John Glen",,"2018-03-05T14:38:46.687Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/851711/answer","Biography information for John Glen","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/851711/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/851711/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2018-02-28","Help to Buy Scheme: Individual Savings Accounts","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what are the eligibility criteria is for a person to qualify for a bonus with a Help to Buy ISA.","false","Biography information for John Woodcock","Barrow and Furness","John Woodcock","130474"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/851712","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-03-05","<p>The spring and autumn Budgets last year announced that over £2.9 billion of additional capital funding will be made available to support NHS Sustainability and Transformation Partnerships in delivering improvements in their infrastructure to support transformation of services, support their ability to better meet demand for local services and drive efficiency improvements.</p><p> </p><p>Provisional funding for the first 37 successful schemes was announced in July and November 2017 and the Government expects to shortly be able to announce the next set of successful schemes from these which have applied for funding. The Halton Health and Wellbeing campus is one of the schemes being considered.</p>","North East Cambridgeshire","Stephen Barclay",,"2018-03-05T16:12:20.08Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/851712/answer","Biography information for Stephen Barclay","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/851712/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/851712/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-02-28","Halton Hospital","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, when he plans to make a decision on the allocation of funding for the proposed Health and Wellbeing campus at the Halton hospital site.","false","Biography information for Derek Twigg","Halton","Derek Twigg","130475"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/851713","Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government","false","2018-03-09","<p>I refer the Hon Member to chapters 11 and 13 of the draft National Planning Policy Framework published for consultation on 5 March.</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/national-planning-policy-framework-and-developer-contribution-consultations" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/national-planning-policy-framework-and-developer-contribution-consultations</a></p>","Esher and Walton","Dominic Raab","130480","2018-03-09T16:47:59.683Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/851713/answer","Biography information for Dominic Raab","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/851713/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/851713/answer","Esher and Walton","Dominic Raab","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/851713/answer/previousversion/44865","Biography information for Dominic Raab","7","Housing, Communities and Local Government","Housing, Communities and Local Government","2018-02-28","Housing: Construction","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Housing, Communities and Local Government, pursuant to oral contribution of the Minister for Housing on 6 February 2018, Official Report, column 1461, whether a local authority with (a) no brownfield land to build on and (b) heavily contaminated land is classified as exceptional circumstances for enabling housebuilding on greenbelt land.","false","Biography information for Derek Twigg","Halton","Derek Twigg","130476"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/851714","HM Treasury","false","2018-03-06","<p>The subcontractor who supplies HM Treasury with its tableware is Baxter Story Plc.</p><p> </p>","Newark","Robert Jenrick",,"2018-03-06T15:02:56.47Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/851714/answer","Biography information for Robert Jenrick","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/851714/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/851714/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2018-02-28","Treasury: Tableware","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, pursuant to the Answer of 28 February 2018 to Question 128648 on Treasury: Tableware, which subcontractors supply his Department with its tableware.","false","Biography information for Ruth Smeeth","Stoke-on-Trent North","Ruth Smeeth","130477"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/851715","Department for Education","false","2018-03-09","<p>Whilst we constantly keep policy under review, we have not had discussions about bringing forward legislative proposals to amend section 1(3).</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Stratford-on-Avon","Nadhim Zahawi",,"2018-03-09T14:54:38.407Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/851715/answer","Biography information for Nadhim Zahawi","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/851715/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/851715/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2018-02-28","Children: Disability","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what discussions he has had with Cabinet colleagues on the potential merits of bringing forward legislative proposals to amend s1.3 of the Children Act 1989 to better define the classification of disability as incapacity to parent.","false","Biography information for Stephen Lloyd","Eastbourne","Stephen Lloyd","130478"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/851716","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2018-03-05","<p>The Independent Case Examiner’s Office has to date received one complaint relating to the equalisation of state pension age from the Halton constituency, which was declined for investigation in February 2018 as the relevant acceptance criteria had not been met.</p>","North West Hampshire","Kit Malthouse",,"2018-03-05T17:59:15.163Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/851716/answer","Biography information for Kit Malthouse","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/851716/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/851716/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2018-02-28","State Retirement Pensions: Halton","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many complaints the Independent Case Examiner is considering from Halton constituency relating to the equalisation of the state pension age; and how many such complaints from Halton constituency that examiner has resolved since 2 October 2017.","false","Biography information for Derek Twigg","Halton","Derek Twigg","130479"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/851717","Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government","false","2018-03-09","<p>I refer the Hon Member to chapters 11 and 13 of the draft National Planning Policy Framework published for consultation on 5 March.</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/national-planning-policy-framework-and-developer-contribution-consultations" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/national-planning-policy-framework-and-developer-contribution-consultations</a></p>","Esher and Walton","Dominic Raab","130476","2018-03-09T16:47:59.76Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/851717/answer","Biography information for Dominic Raab","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/851717/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/851717/answer","Esher and Walton","Dominic Raab","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/851717/answer/previousversion/44871","Biography information for Dominic Raab","7","Housing, Communities and Local Government","Housing, Communities and Local Government","2018-02-28","Housing: Construction","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Housing, Communities and Local Government, pursuant to the oral contribution of the Minister for Housing on 6 February 2018, Official Report, column 1461, whether he has to empower local authorities to prevent developers from building on greenbelt when allocated brownfield sites have not been developed.","false","Biography information for Derek Twigg","Halton","Derek Twigg","130480"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/851718","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2018-03-05","<p>Disability Confident helps employers to improve in their ability to recruit, retain and develop disabled people. Over 5500 employers have joined the scheme to date. Disability Confident employers make specific commitments, offering a range of job opportunities, work experience, work trials, supported internships etc.</p><p> </p><p>As an example of its impact, since becoming Disability Confident, Fujitsu has significantly increased the number of people with disabilities on its graduate recruitment programme. 20% of the cohort last September had disabilities. Fujitsu has also seen an increase in the number of employees declaring they have a disability, which allows the company to better provide adjustments or support.</p><p> </p><p>The number of disabled people in work has increased by around 600,000 since 2013.</p>","Truro and Falmouth","Sarah Newton",,"2018-03-05T17:29:57.38Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/851718/answer","Biography information for Sarah Newton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/851718/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/851718/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2018-02-28","Employment: Disability","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what information her Department holds on how many disabled people have found work as a direct result of the Disability Confident campaign.","false","Biography information for Marsha De Cordova","Battersea","Marsha De Cordova","130481"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/851719","Ministry of Justice","false","2018-03-09","<p>The government is committed to making sure that victims of crime have access to a broad range of support services, to help them cope with and, as far as possible, recover from the effects of crime. In 2016/17 we spent about £96m to fund support services for victims of crime.</p><p> </p><p>Just over £3.2m of this was allocated to Greater Manchester and about £64.4m was allocated to all Police and Crime Commissioners in England to locally commission or provide support services for victims of crime, including for victims of offences related to domestic abuse.</p><p> </p><p>In 2016/17 Greater Manchester reported spending just under £0.7m on services to support victims of domestic abuse and Police and Crime Commissioners in England reported spending about £11.1m on services to support victims of domestic abuse.</p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2018-03-09T14:06:50.517Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/851719/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/851719/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/851719/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2018-02-28","Domestic Abuse","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what support his Department provides to women who engage with the criminal justice system as a result of domestic abuse in (a) Greater Manchester and (b) England.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","130482"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/851720","Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government","false","2018-03-06","<p>The Government recognises the life changing impact domestic abuse can have on the lives of children. We will introduce a landmark draft Domestic Abuse Bill to protect and support victims, recognise the life-long impact domestic abuse has on children and make sure agencies effectively respond to domestic abuse.</p><p>The Government is determined to tackle violence against women and girls and the Home Secretary chairs an Inter-Ministerial Group on this issue on which both the Department for Education and Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government are represented.</p><p>Through our 2015 £3.5 million fund and our 2016/18 £20 million fund for domestic abuse services, the Ministry for Housing, Communities and Local Government have funded projects to improve support for children who have experienced domestic abuse.</p><p>The Department for Education has invested around £900,000 from December 2016 to March 2018 in voluntary sector projects to address domestic abuse and its impact on children.</p><p>The Government has also invested £920 million in the Troubled Families Programme, to support up to 400,000 families with multiple high-cost problems, including domestic abuse, by 2020.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","South Derbyshire","Mrs Heather Wheeler",,"2018-03-06T12:46:54.437Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/851720/answer","Biography information for Mrs Heather Wheeler","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/851720/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/851720/answer",,,,,"7","Housing, Communities and Local Government","Housing, Communities and Local Government","2018-02-28","Refuges: Children","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Housing, Communities and Local Government, what joint initiatives his Department has with the Department for Education on supporting a child whose parent enters a women's refuge.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","130483"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/851721","Department for Education","false","2018-03-09","<p>Under section 17 of the Children Act 1989, every local authority has a duty to safeguard and promote the welfare of children within their area who are in need, by providing a range and level of services appropriate to those children’s needs. If a child joins the parent in a refuge, the duty would lie with the local authority where the refuge is situated, by virtue of the child being in their area. This would apply to Manchester as to any other authority.</p>","Stratford-on-Avon","Nadhim Zahawi",,"2018-03-09T09:49:54.4Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/851721/answer","Biography information for Nadhim Zahawi","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/851721/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/851721/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2018-02-28","Children: Refuges","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what support his Department provides for a child whose parent enters a women's refuge in (a) Greater Manchester and (b) England.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","130484"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/851722","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-03-05","<p>NHS Protect commenced their enquiries into this matter on 12 February 2015. The counter fraud functions of NHS Protect were taken over by the NHS Counter Fraud Authority on 1 November 2017.</p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage",,"2018-03-05T17:27:56.78Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/851722/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/851722/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/851722/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-02-28","Phil Morely","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, with reference to the Answer of 24 February 2017 to Question 63667 and the Answer of 22 February 2018 to Question, on what date NHS Protect's investigation into Phil Morley began.","false","Biography information for Diana Johnson","Kingston upon Hull North","Diana Johnson","130485"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/851723","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-03-08","<p>The National Health Service leadership bodies have developed their own plan for delivering financial balance and sustainability for the NHS. We support that plan and through the 2015 Spending Review, the Government committed to a real terms increase of £10 billion in NHS funding by 2020-21, compared to 2014/15. But it is for local leaders in Sustainability and Transformation Partnership areas, working together with NHS England and NHS Improvement, to deliver against their own plans to achieve financial sustainability.</p><p> </p><p>We are keenly aware that local issues exist within the national plan, but as with all public services, local NHS areas need to live within their means. NHS England and NHS Improvement will continue to work with areas to balance their financial plans.</p>","Winchester","Steve Brine",,"2018-03-08T15:10:40.54Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/851723/answer","Biography information for Steve Brine","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/851723/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/851723/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-02-28","Halton Clinical Commissioning Group","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, what recent assessment his Department has made of the financial sustainability of Halton Clinical Commissioning Group.","false","Biography information for Derek Twigg","Halton","Derek Twigg","130486"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/851724","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-03-05","<p>Dr Andrew Davies was appointed as Chief Officer with an effective start date of 1 February 2018. This appointment has been made as a result of the interim Chief Officer’s move to a Sustainability and Transformation Partnership role.</p><p> </p><p>At present, this appointment is considered to be on an interim basis and does not have an end date.</p>","Winchester","Steve Brine",,"2018-03-05T15:53:05.047Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/851724/answer","Biography information for Steve Brine","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/851724/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/851724/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-02-28","Halton Clinical Commissioning Group","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, what the timescale is for appointing a new chief officer to Halton Clinical Commissioning Group.","false","Biography information for Derek Twigg","Halton","Derek Twigg","130487"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/851725","Department for Education","false","2018-03-05","<p>Capital funding for open free schools, university technical colleges and studios schools, where costs have been finalised, are published on GOV.UK at: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/capital-funding-for-open-free-schools" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/capital-funding-for-open-free-schools</a>. For reasons of commercial confidentiality, the capital costs of individual schools are not disclosed before completion and overall costs are finalised.</p><p> </p><p>The site was acquired for £3 million, but final overall capital costs are yet to be finalised. Completion for Route 39 will be in August 2018 and the costs for the school will be published after this.</p><p> </p><p>Additional finalised capital costs are due to be published in the coming months.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2018-03-05T17:32:59.737Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/851725/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/851725/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/851725/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2018-02-28","Route 39 Academy Bideford","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what the cost to the public purse was of the capital funding his Department provided for the Route 39 free school in North Devon.","false","Biography information for Angela Rayner","Ashton-under-Lyne","Angela Rayner","130488"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/851726","Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government","false","2018-03-08","<p>The Interim report of Dame Judith Hackitt’s Independent Review of Building Regulations and Fire Safety made the following recommendation;</p><p>&quot;The government should significantly restrict the use of desktop studies to approve changes to cladding and other systems to ensure that they are only used where appropriate and with sufficient, relevant test evidence. Those undertaking desktop studies must be able to demonstrate suitable competence. The industry should ensure that their use of desktop studies is responsible and in line with this aim.&quot;</p><p>The government has accepted this recommendation and will be consulting shortly on proposed changes to building regulations guidance.</p>","Esher and Walton","Dominic Raab",,"2018-03-08T12:02:05.197Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/851726/answer","Biography information for Dominic Raab","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/851726/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/851726/answer","Esher and Walton","Dominic Raab","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/851726/answer/previousversion/44856","Biography information for Dominic Raab","7","Housing, Communities and Local Government","Housing, Communities and Local Government","2018-02-28","Buildings: Fire Prevention","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Housing, Communities and Local Government, what assessment his Department has made of the suitability of using desktop studies to assess the flammability of cladding on buildings.","false","Biography information for Dr Rosena Allin-Khan","Tooting","Dr Rosena Allin-Khan","130489"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/851727","HM Treasury","false","2018-03-09","<p>International treaties ensure that there is no taxation of international aviation fuel, and the Government does not levy VAT on flights. APD ensures the aviation sector contributes its fair share to general taxation. Even at the current rates of APD, UK airports have enjoyed strong passenger growth: exceeding 15% in the previous five years.</p><p>The Government has not conducted an assessment of route opportunities under the specific scenarios mentioned. However, the Government is working with the sector to understand better how they believe any reduced APD rates might support new routes and increase connectivity.</p><p>The government will also look at the effects of APD and VAT on tourism in Northern Ireland. A call for evidence on this issue was announced at Autumn Budget 2017 and will be published in due course. Respondents in the aviation industry will be able to submit evidence on the wider impacts of APD upon UK tourism.</p>","Newark","Robert Jenrick","130357 ; 130358 ; 130359","2018-03-09T11:15:57.917Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/851727/answer","Biography information for Robert Jenrick","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/851727/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/851727/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2018-02-28","Air Passenger Duty","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what assessment he has made of the effect of reducing Air Passenger Duty by 50 per cent on (a) the number of passenger journeys and (b) air routes.","false","Biography information for Mr Nigel Evans","Ribble Valley","Mr Nigel Evans","130490"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/851728","Department for Education","false","2018-03-09","<p>Capital funding for individual free schools, university technical colleges (UTCs) and studio schools, where costs have been finalised and are no longer commercially sensitive, are published on GOV.UK at: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/capital-funding-for-open-free-schools" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/capital-funding-for-open-free-schools</a>. Additional finalised capital costs for individual free schools, UTCs and studio schools are due to be published in the coming months.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb","130492 ; 130493 ; 130498 ; 130524 ; 130527","2018-03-09T09:42:47.707Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/851728/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/851728/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/851728/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2018-02-28","Southwark Free School","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what the cost to the public purse was of the capital funding provided for the Southwark Free School.","false","Biography information for Angela Rayner","Ashton-under-Lyne","Angela Rayner","130491"
