"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850817","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-03-07","<p>Information is shown in the following table which is a count of finished admission episodes (FAEs), with a primary diagnosis of brain injury, for National Health Service Hospitals within England, for the 2016-17 financial year.</p><p> </p><p>This is a count of hospital episodes, not individual patients, as the same person may have been admitted into an NHS hospital on more than one occasion.</p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Diagnosis Description</p></td><td><p>Hospital admissions 2016-17</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Concussion</p></td><td><p>2,318</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Traumatic cerebral oedema</p></td><td><p>76</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Diffuse brain injury</p></td><td><p>2,410</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Focal brain injury</p></td><td><p>1,277</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Epidural haemorrhage</p></td><td><p>1,072</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Traumatic subdural haemorrhage</p></td><td><p>11,966</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Traumatic subarachnoid haemorrhage</p></td><td><p>4,801</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Intracranial injury with prolonged coma</p></td><td><p>5</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Other intracranial injuries</p></td><td><p>1,845</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Intracranial injury, unspecified</p></td><td><p>386</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p>Source: Hospital Episode Statistics, NHS Digital</p><p> </p><p>Notes:</p><p> </p><ol><li>A FAE is the first period of inpatient care under one consultant within one healthcare provider. FAEs are counted against the year or month in which the admission episode finishes.</li></ol><p> </p><ol start="2"><li>It is not possible to include information surrounding all brain related injuries due to the volume of conditions this could potentially include.</li></ol>","North East Cambridgeshire","Stephen Barclay",,"2018-03-07T17:47:13.887Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850817/answer","Biography information for Stephen Barclay","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850817/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850817/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-02-27","Hospitals: Admissions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, how many people were admitted to an NHS hospital in England with a brain injury or related condition in 2017.","false","Biography information for Robert Halfon","Harlow","Robert Halfon","130045"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850818","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-03-07","<p>Information is shown in the following table which is a count of finished discharged episodes (FDEs)<sup>1</sup> with a spell duration<sup>2</sup> of seven days or longer in National Health Service hospitals for the financial year 2016-17.</p><p>This is a count of hospital episodes, not individual patients, as the same person may have been admitted into an NHS hospital on more than one occasion.</p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Year</p></td><td><p>Total FDEs</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2016-17</p></td><td><p>1,596,412</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p>Source: Hospital Episode Statistics, NHS Digital</p><p> </p><p>Notes:</p><ol><li>A FDE indicates whether the episode is a finished discharge episode (whether the patient was discharged at the end of the episode).</li><li>The difference in days between the admission date and the discharge date, where both dates are given.</li></ol>","North East Cambridgeshire","Stephen Barclay",,"2018-03-07T10:42:18.31Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850818/answer","Biography information for Stephen Barclay","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850818/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850818/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-02-27","Hospitals: Admissions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, how many patients stayed at an NHS hospital in England for seven days or longer in 2017.","false","Biography information for Robert Halfon","Harlow","Robert Halfon","130046"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850819","Attorney General","false","2018-03-13","<p>The Crown Prosecution Service (CPS) does not maintain a central record of the number of prosecutions for personal injury insurance frauds. Nor is any record held to show if defendants were purporting to have sustained an injury on a road when making a fraudulent claim. This information could only be obtained by examining CPS case files, which would incur disproportionate cost.</p>","South Swindon","Robert Buckland",,"2018-03-13T11:03:30.243Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850819/answer","Biography information for Robert Buckland","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850819/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850819/answer",,,,,"88","Attorney General","Attorney General","2018-02-27","Personal Injury: Fraud","1","House of Commons","To ask the Attorney General, how many proven fraudulent personal injury claims were made by (a) horse-riders, (b) pedestrians, (c) cyclists and (d) other vulnerable road users in the last 12 months.","false","Biography information for Ellie Reeves","Lewisham West and Penge","Ellie Reeves","130047"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850820","Attorney General","false","2018-03-13","<p>The Crown Prosecution Service (CPS) does not maintain a central record of the number of prosecutions for personal injury insurance frauds. Nor is any record held to show if defendants were purporting to have sustained an injury on a road when making a fraudulent claim. This information could only be obtained by examining CPS case files, which would incur disproportionate cost.</p>","South Swindon","Robert Buckland",,"2018-03-13T11:03:52.677Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850820/answer","Biography information for Robert Buckland","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850820/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850820/answer",,,,,"88","Attorney General","Attorney General","2018-02-27","Personal Injury: Fraud","1","House of Commons","To ask the Attorney General, how many successful prosecutions there have been for personal injury insurance fraud in the UK court system in the last 12 months.","false","Biography information for Ellie Reeves","Lewisham West and Penge","Ellie Reeves","130048"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850821","Home Office","false","2018-03-07","<p>As a result of the world-leading provisions in the Modern Slavery Act 2015, we have seen thousands of transparency statements published and businesses are now more focused on this issue than ever before. The legislation was designed to harness pressure from civil society and we are pleased that NGOs are using company statements to hold businesses to account, including contacting businesses that have not yet published statements.</p><p>The Government does not monitor compliance with section 54 of the Modern Slavery Act 2015. Two independent repository websites have been set up to collate these statements. The Government is not involved in running or funding either website. Both websites make different estimates of the total number of statements published so far. The latest estimates can be accessed online at <a href="http://www.modernslaveryregistry.org/" target="_blank">http://www.modernslaveryregistry.org/</a> and <a href="https://tiscreport.org/" target="_blank">https://tiscreport.org/</a></p><p>The Government has strengthened guidance for businesses and recently wrote to over 10,000 businesses that may be required to publish statements reminding them of their obligations and providing useful resources. We expect this activity will further increase the number of statements published.</p><p>In October the Government also launched a new ‘Business Against Slavery Forum’. This aims to establish a new partnership between Government and business to accelerate progress in tackling modern slavery. It will focus on sharing best practice and building new initiatives to tackle modern slavery, including improving business engagement with the Modern Slavery Act</p>","Louth and Horncastle","Victoria Atkins","129997","2018-03-07T17:44:34.153Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850821/answer","Biography information for Victoria Atkins","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850821/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850821/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2018-02-27","Slavery","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many businesses have failed to comply with the requirement under the Modern Slavery Act 2015 that every organisation carrying on a business in the UK with a total annual turnover of £36m produce a slavery and human trafficking statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Barry Sheerman","Huddersfield","Mr Barry Sheerman","130049"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850822","Ministry of Justice","false","2018-03-07","<p>The information requested could only be obtained at disproportionate cost.</p>","South East Cambridgeshire","Lucy Frazer",,"2018-03-07T17:27:40.013Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850822/answer","Biography information for Lucy Frazer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850822/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850822/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2018-02-27","Personal Injury: Legal Representation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many litigants in person pursued personal injury cases in the courts in each of the last 5 years.","false","Biography information for Ellie Reeves","Lewisham West and Penge","Ellie Reeves","130050"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850823","Ministry of Justice","false","2018-03-07","<p>The Association of British Insurers’ most recent public assessment suggests that the level of detected insurance claims fraud (including road traffic accidents) was £1.3 billion in 2016. The Government is aware of fraud in package holiday sickness claims and is taking action to address it.</p>","South East Cambridgeshire","Lucy Frazer",,"2018-03-07T17:27:15.057Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850823/answer","Biography information for Lucy Frazer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850823/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850823/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2018-02-27","Personal Injury: Fraud","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what recent assessment his Department has made of the level of proven fraud or exaggeration in non-road traffic accident injury claims.","false","Biography information for Ellie Reeves","Lewisham West and Penge","Ellie Reeves","130051"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850825","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2018-03-06","<p>Please find below the volumes of personal injury claims submitted and registered with DWP Compensation Recovery Unit for the last five complete financial years which is how we record this Information:</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Financial Year</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Claims Registered</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2016/17</p></td><td><p>978,816</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015/16</p></td><td><p>981,324</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014/15</p></td><td><p>998,359</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013/14</p></td><td><p>1,016,801</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2012/13</p></td><td><p>1,048,309</p></td></tr></tbody></table>","North West Hampshire","Kit Malthouse",,"2018-03-06T11:16:41.693Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850825/answer","Biography information for Kit Malthouse","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850825/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850825/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2018-02-27","Personal Injury: Compensation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many personal injury claims were submitted to the Compensation Recovery Unit in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Ellie Reeves","Lewisham West and Penge","Ellie Reeves","130052"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850826","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2018-03-05","<p>I refer my hon. Friend to the reply given to him on 12 February 2018, PQ 126545.</p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey",,"2018-03-05T13:09:47.577Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850826/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850826/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850826/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2018-02-27","Smoke Control Areas","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what estimate he has made of the amount spent by local authorities in the UK on Smoke Control Area enforcement in each year since 1992 up to the latest year for which data is available; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Philip Davies","Shipley","Philip Davies","130053"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850827","Department for International Development","false","2018-03-06","<p>Promoting jobs where workers’ rights are upheld, living wages are paid, and they are free from exploitation, is fundamental for alleviating poverty. The Ethical Trading Initiative’s Base Code is an important standard for companies to aim for, which is why DFID has provided ETI with a £5.1M grant and is encouraging its suppliers to sign up to it.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2018-03-06T14:14:38.757Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850827/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850827/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850827/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2018-02-27","Ethical Trading Initiative","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what steps the Government is taking to encourage businesses to comply with the Ethical Trading Initiative Base Code.","false","Biography information for Mr Barry Sheerman","Huddersfield","Mr Barry Sheerman","130054"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850828","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-03-07","<p>NHS Digital publishes data on the nationality of staff working in the National Health Service in England and the latest figures show that there were over 3,200 more European Union nationals working in the NHS in September 2017 than before the referendum result.</p><p>The Government is committed to ensuring that the NHS and social care system have the nurses, midwives, doctors, carers and other health professionals that it needs<em>.</em></p><p>We continue to monitor and analyse overall staffing levels across the NHS and adult social care, and we are working across Government to ensure there will continue to be sufficient staff to deliver the high quality services on which patients rely following the United Kingdom’s exit from the EU.</p><p>On 8 December, the UK and EU Commission reached an agreement which delivered on the Prime Minister’s number one priority, to safeguard the rights of people who have built their lives in the UK and EU, following the UK’s exit from the EU.</p><p>The agreement will guarantee the rights of the 150,000 EU nationals working in our health and care system. It means that EU citizens living lawfully in the UK and UK nationals living lawfully in the EU by 29 March 2019 will be able to stay and enjoy broadly the same rights and benefits as they do now.</p>","North East Cambridgeshire","Stephen Barclay","130123","2018-03-07T10:39:47.087Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850828/answer","Biography information for Stephen Barclay","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850828/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850828/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-02-27","NHS: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, what assessment his Department has made of the effect of the UK leaving the EU on staffing levels in the NHS.","false","Biography information for Hugh Gaffney","Coatbridge, Chryston and Bellshill","Hugh Gaffney","130055"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850829","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2018-03-07","<p>​The Foreign and Commonwealth Office stands ready to support the Electoral Commission in their statutory duty to promote electoral registration among British citizens overseas, including if the Overseas Electors Bill is passed into law.</p>","Rutland and Melton","Sir Alan Duncan",,"2018-03-07T14:59:39.237Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850829/answer","Biography information for Sir Alan Duncan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850829/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850829/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2018-02-27","British Nationals Abroad: Voting Rights","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, whether UK embassies in EU 27 countries are making preparations to engage with British citizens overseas in the event that the Overseas Electors Bill is passed into law.","false","Biography information for Andy Slaughter","Hammersmith","Andy Slaughter","130056"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850831","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2018-03-05","<p>The Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs has not visited the border between Northern Ireland and the Republic of Ireland since his appointment as Foreign Secretary. He has visited the border several times prior to becoming Foreign Secretary, both before and after the Belfast Agreement was agreed and implemented. He last visited Ireland on 16-17 November 2017.</p>","Rutland and Melton","Sir Alan Duncan",,"2018-03-05T17:40:14.93Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850831/answer","Biography information for Sir Alan Duncan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850831/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850831/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2018-02-27","Borders: Northern Ireland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, when he last visited the border between Northern Ireland and the Republic of Ireland.","false","Biography information for Wes Streeting","Ilford North","Wes Streeting","130057"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850832","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-03-06","<p>Providers of National Health Service-funded healthcare services are expected to meet a range of waiting time standards and other operational standards and quality requirements, in order to deliver the rights and pledges in the NHS Constitution and to achieve other national priorities. These requirements are set out in the NHS Standard Contract, which is used by clinical commissioning groups (CCGs) for all contracts with hospital providers of NHS healthcare services. The Contract sets out the consequences of breaches of the waiting time standards and other requirements. In many cases, this consequence is in the form of a financial sanction.</p><p> </p><p>However, since April 2016, the operation of certain contractual sanctions for reduced performance against waiting time standards, including four hour and 12 hour waits in accident and emergency (A&amp;E) and the Referral to Treatment 18 week incomplete pathways standard has been suspended where a provider is receiving funding from the national Sustainability and Transformation Fund (STF) and meets certain other specified conditions. The overall effect is that, in 2017/18, the Contract sanctions for A&amp;E performance are not being applied to the majority of NHS hospitals – only to a very small minority which refused the offer of funding from the STF and the associated conditions.</p><p> </p><p>Since 2015/16, NHS Improvement has published a high level summary of this information in their Quarterly reports, the latest of which is for Quarter 3 of 2017/18 and is available at the following link:</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://improvement.nhs.uk/resources/quarterly-performance-nhs-provider-sector-quarter-3-201718/" target="_blank">https://improvement.nhs.uk/resources/quarterly-performance-nhs-provider-sector-quarter-3-201718/</a></p>","North East Cambridgeshire","Stephen Barclay","130060 ; 130061","2018-03-06T14:00:23.727Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850832/answer","Biography information for Stephen Barclay","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850832/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850832/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-02-27","Hospitals: Standards","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, how much money NHS hospitals have been fined for not reaching targets in the last five financial years.","false","Biography information for Gareth Johnson","Dartford","Gareth Johnson","130058"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850833","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2018-03-05","<p>​The Foreign Secretary has been in regular contact with his Turkish counterpart, Foreign Minister Çavuşoğlu, and has encouraged de-escalation in Afrin and the protection of civilians, while recognising Turkey's legitimate security interests. In line with UNSCR 2401, the UK urgently wants to see the safe, unimpeded and sustained delivery of humanitarian aid and services across the country, and medical evacuations of the critically sick and wounded, in accordance with applicable international law.</p>","Rutland and Melton","Sir Alan Duncan",,"2018-03-05T17:35:23.723Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850833/answer","Biography information for Sir Alan Duncan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850833/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850833/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2018-02-27","Syria: Armed Conflict","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what recent discussions he has had with his Turkish counterpart on the implementation of a ceasefire in the Afrin region as a result of UN Resolution 2401.","false","Biography information for Joan Ryan","Enfield North","Joan Ryan","130059"
